    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>CANADIAN MINING DEAL</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Timothy Pritchard</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Pritchard, Timothy</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Canada's Noranda Inc makes offer of $1.02 billion for Rio Algom Mines Ltd; photo (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>The Canadian mining and metals producer Noranda Inc. made an offer of $1.02 billion for Rio Algom Mines Ltd., a domestic rival, that is intended to strengthen its copper holdings in South America. Toronto-based Noranda is offering 24.50 Canadian dollars in cash -- a total of 1.5 billion Canadian dollars -- for each Rio Algom share. Noranda's chief executive, David Kerr, said, ''This is a very good transaction for Nornada and establishes an important partnership with the world's largest copper producer.''</p>
        <p>Timothy Pritchard</p>
      </block>
